#28) before deleting --> [http://www.paxlibrorum.com/books/histories/ The Histories of Herodotus], A.D. Godley translation with footnotes ({{cite web|url= http://www.paxlibrorum.com/res/downloads/histories_5by8.pdf |title=Direct link to PDF }}&nbsp;{{small|(14&nbsp;MB)}})\n{{Ancient Greece topics|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Herodotus| ]]\n[[Category:480s BC births]]\n[[Category:420s BC deaths]]\n[[Category:5th-century BC Greek people]]\n[[Category:5th-century BC historians]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek political refugees]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greeks in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Ancient Halicarnassians]]\n[[Category:Classical-era Greek historians]]\n[[Category:History of Asia]]\n[[Category:Historians from ancient Anatolia]]\n[[Category:Historiography of India]]\n[[Category:Ionic Greek writers]]\n[[Category:Sources of ancient Iranian religion]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greeks from the Achaemenid Empire]]\n[[Category:Historians of the Achaemenid Empire]]\n", "name_user": "2603:9000:2501:b347:593e:9c5c:d259:1707", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herodotus"}
{"title_page": "Seniority", "text_new": "{{For|the order of repayment in the event of bankruptcy|Seniority (financial)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2009}}\n'''Seniority''' is the concept of a person or group of people taking precedence over another person or group because the former is either older than the latter or has occupied a particular position longer than the latter. Seniority is present between parents and children and may be present in other common relationships, such as among siblings of different ages or between workers and their managers.\nThe fact of something being it's sincerely\nUnder a seniority system, control is often granted to senior persons due to length of service in a given position. When persons of senior rank have less length of service than their subordinates, \"seniority\" may apply to either concept.\n\n== In armed forces ==<!--linked from [[Adrian Johns]]-->\n\nIn some military [[command structure]]s, the length of time someone has held a particular rank is called \"seniority in grade\" and determines whether that person is senior to another person of the same [[military rank|rank]]. For instance, a captain who was promoted five years ago can give orders to a captain who was promoted three years ago.\n\n== In politics ==\n\nSeniority in [[United States politics]], when used out of context, is informally defined as the number of years one member of a group has been a part of the group. For example, as of January 2015, [[John Conyers]] from [[Michigan]] is the most senior member of the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]].<ref>http://pressgallery.house.gov/member-data/seniority</ref> However, \"seniority\" can also refer to political power attained by position within the United States Government. For further details, see:\n* [[United States Order of Precedence]]\n* [[United States Presidential Line of Succession]]\n* [[Seniority in the United States Senate]]\n* [[Dean of the United States House of Representatives]]\nSeniority is viewed sometimes both positively and negatively. Many elected officials are viewed as retaining their position only because they have been there for many years, which can reflect voter stagnancy and the benefits of incumbency. On the other hand, long years of [[Incumbent|incumbency]] can also be seen as a sign of the person's ability to continue pleasing voters or the use of seniority to deliver benefits to constituents.\n\nIn some countries the [[Dean of the Diplomatic Corps]] receives special treatment.\n\n== In employment ==\nIn [[trade union|unionised]] companies, employees with more seniority may enjoy more work privileges.<ref>https://smallbusiness.chron.com/seniority-important-union-13338.html</ref> Here are examples: \n* [[Shift work]] at more favourable times\n* Work that is deemed easier or more pleasurable\n* Working hours at a more convenient time (convenience being relative to the employee)\n* Assignment to work, when a work reduction, or a reduction in available work hours results in layoffs\n\nSeniority also has an influence over [[bump (union)|bumping]] rights, which is a reassignment of jobs, possibly for many people at a time.\n\nSome traditionalist employers, common in smaller, single-operated business, take a \"last in, first out\" ([[LIFO (education)|LIFO]]) perspective, meaning those who have been there longest or who have [[tenure]] have the right to stay, whereas other employers take a \"first in, first out\" ([[FIFO (disambiguation)|FIFO]]) or \"inverse seniority\" viewpoint, which tends to emphasize a new or \"fresh start\" for the company.<ref>https://www.thebalancecareers.com/what-seniority-means-at-work-1919372</ref>\n\nSeniority does have several positive factors to its name.  Individuals may be drawn toward a specific field or occupation with the knowledge that seniority is obtainable.  If seniority were to be banished as a whole, many higher paid employees would be fired first just because they make more money than their peers.  Seniority does an effective job in helping people, interested in staying at one organization, in working towards having a \"marathon\" career.  One of the goals of a seniority system is [[employee retention]], which ensures an organization is retaining institutional knowledge, erudite employees, and an opportunity for [[mentorship]] of new hires.  It's important to make sure employees are here to stay. \n\nThough the principle of seniority does an effective job of protecting long-term employees, in some scenarios, it can fail to address several critical factors.  Firstly, spots secured by seniority casts aside some of the most appealing perspectives.  Individuals will become less driven to enter a field that does not reinforce their efforts with employment.  Secondly, the security of [[tenure]] often encourages mediocrity. <ref>https://www.bankrate.com/finance/personal-finance/pros-cons-union-jobs-1.aspx</ref> Employees with the knowledge that their spot in the workplace is secured will naturally become less likely to improve their working ethics as they may no longer view improvement as a necessity.  Lastly, a system rewarding individuals for their hiring date does not encourage professional growth.  If individuals are aware they only have to reach a certain time-span of employment to have a guaranteed position in a company, they will not grow professionally once they have reached their mark.   <ref>https://huffingtonpost.com/heather-wolpertgawron/pros-and-cons-of-the-seni_b_831740.html</ref>\n\nDuring the late 20th century in the United States, the federal government stopped emphasizing seniority as the primary basis for pay raises for its workforce.  The Reagan administration replaced a seniority-based system for pay increases for its white collar government workers.  The new system included [[Performance appraisal|performance appraisal]]. <ref>https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1987-12-06-8703310962-story.html</ref>\n\n=== In transport ===\n[[Commercial aviation]] pilots working for a carrier have their privileges determined by their seniority or generally known as the \"pilot seniority list.\" These privileges can be income level, routes flown, types of aircraft, work schedules and positions.<ref>http://www.airlineempires.net/blog/2008/03/pilot-seniority-101-part-1-the-sacred-cow/</ref><ref>http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/business/6984637.html</ref><ref>http://science.howstuffworks.com/pilot6.htm</ref><ref>http://science.howstuffworks.com/pilot7.htm</ref> Seniority is most important when deciding which pilots to upgrade to a larger, more complex aircraft type; or for upgrading a [[First Officer (civil aviation)|First Officer]] to the rank of a [[Captain (civil aviation)|Captain]].\n\n[[Engine driver]]s with many [[railway]]s also have a seniority list, but it is focused on work scheduling. Younger engine drivers often serve as back-up personnel and must help out on a very short notice \u2013 for example when a colleague calls in sick or has a delay.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Authority]]\n*[[Buggins' turn]]\n*[[Father of the House]]\n*[[Filial piety]]\n*[[Gerontocracy]]\n*[[Gerousia]]\n*[[Hierarchy]]\n*[[Lockstep compensation]]\n*[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives]]\n*[[Seniority in the United States Senate]]\n*[[Superior (hierarchy)]]\n*[[Tenure]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Political philosophy]]\n[[Category:Hierarchy]]\n[[Category:Personnel economics]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the order of repayment in the event of bankruptcy|Seniority (financial)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2009}}\n'''Seniority''' is the concept of a person or group of people taking precedence over another person or group because the former is either older than the latter or has occupied a particular position longer than the latter. Seniority is present between parents and children and may be present in other common relationships, such as among siblings of different ages or between workers and their managers.\n\nUnder a seniority system, control is often granted to senior persons due to length of service in a given position. When persons of senior rank have less length of service than their subordinates, \"seniority\" may apply to either concept.\n\n== In armed forces ==<!--linked from [[Adrian Johns]]-->\n\nIn some military [[command structure]]s, the length of time someone has held a particular rank is called \"seniority in grade\" and determines whether that person is senior to another person of the same [[military rank|rank]]. For instance, a captain who was promoted five years ago can give orders to a captain who was promoted three years ago.\n\n== In politics ==\n\nSeniority in [[United States politics]], when used out of context, is informally defined as the number of years one member of a group has been a part of the group. For example, as of January 2015, [[John Conyers]] from [[Michigan]] is the most senior member of the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]].<ref>http://pressgallery.house.gov/member-data/seniority</ref> However, \"seniority\" can also refer to political power attained by position within the United States Government. For further details, see:\n* [[United States Order of Precedence]]\n* [[United States Presidential Line of Succession]]\n* [[Seniority in the United States Senate]]\n* [[Dean of the United States House of Representatives]]\nSeniority is viewed sometimes both positively and negatively. Many elected officials are viewed as retaining their position only because they have been there for many years, which can reflect voter stagnancy and the benefits of incumbency. On the other hand, long years of [[Incumbent|incumbency]] can also be seen as a sign of the person's ability to continue pleasing voters or the use of seniority to deliver benefits to constituents.\n\nIn some countries the [[Dean of the Diplomatic Corps]] receives special treatment.\n\n== In employment ==\nIn [[trade union|unionised]] companies, employees with more seniority may enjoy more work privileges.<ref>https://smallbusiness.chron.com/seniority-important-union-13338.html</ref> Here are examples: \n* [[Shift work]] at more favourable times\n* Work that is deemed easier or more pleasurable\n* Working hours at a more convenient time (convenience being relative to the employee)\n* Assignment to work, when a work reduction, or a reduction in available work hours results in layoffs\n\nSeniority also has an influence over [[bump (union)|bumping]] rights, which is a reassignment of jobs, possibly for many people at a time.\n\nSome traditionalist employers, common in smaller, single-operated business, take a \"last in, first out\" ([[LIFO (education)|LIFO]]) perspective, meaning those who have been there longest or who have [[tenure]] have the right to stay, whereas other employers take a \"first in, first out\" ([[FIFO (disambiguation)|FIFO]]) or \"inverse seniority\" viewpoint, which tends to emphasize a new or \"fresh start\" for the company.<ref>https://www.thebalancecareers.com/what-seniority-means-at-work-1919372</ref>\n\nSeniority does have several positive factors to its name.  Individuals may be drawn toward a specific field or occupation with the knowledge that seniority is obtainable.  If seniority were to be banished as a whole, many higher paid employees would be fired first just because they make more money than their peers.  Seniority does an effective job in helping people, interested in staying at one organization, in working towards having a \"marathon\" career.  One of the goals of a seniority system is [[employee retention]], which ensures an organization is retaining institutional knowledge, erudite employees, and an opportunity for [[mentorship]] of new hires.  It's important to make sure employees are here to stay. \n\nThough the principle of seniority does an effective job of protecting long-term employees, in some scenarios, it can fail to address several critical factors.  Firstly, spots secured by seniority casts aside some of the most appealing perspectives.  Individuals will become less driven to enter a field that does not reinforce their efforts with employment.  Secondly, the security of [[tenure]] often encourages mediocrity. <ref>https://www.bankrate.com/finance/personal-finance/pros-cons-union-jobs-1.aspx</ref> Employees with the knowledge that their spot in the workplace is secured will naturally become less likely to improve their working ethics as they may no longer view improvement as a necessity.  Lastly, a system rewarding individuals for their hiring date does not encourage professional growth.  If individuals are aware they only have to reach a certain time-span of employment to have a guaranteed position in a company, they will not grow professionally once they have reached their mark.   <ref>https://huffingtonpost.com/heather-wolpertgawron/pros-and-cons-of-the-seni_b_831740.html</ref>\n\nDuring the late 20th century in the United States, the federal government stopped emphasizing seniority as the primary basis for pay raises for its workforce.  The Reagan administration replaced a seniority-based system for pay increases for its white collar government workers.  The new system included [[Performance appraisal|performance appraisal]]. <ref>https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1987-12-06-8703310962-story.html</ref>\n\n=== In transport ===\n[[Commercial aviation]] pilots working for a carrier have their privileges determined by their seniority or generally known as the \"pilot seniority list.\" These privileges can be income level, routes flown, types of aircraft, work schedules and positions.<ref>http://www.airlineempires.net/blog/2008/03/pilot-seniority-101-part-1-the-sacred-cow/</ref><ref>http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/business/6984637.html</ref><ref>http://science.howstuffworks.com/pilot6.htm</ref><ref>http://science.howstuffworks.com/pilot7.htm</ref> Seniority is most important when deciding which pilots to upgrade to a larger, more complex aircraft type; or for upgrading a [[First Officer (civil aviation)|First Officer]] to the rank of a [[Captain (civil aviation)|Captain]].\n\n[[Engine driver]]s with many [[railway]]s also have a seniority list, but it is focused on work scheduling. Younger engine drivers often serve as back-up personnel and must help out on a very short notice \u2013 for example when a colleague calls in sick or has a delay.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Authority]]\n*[[Buggins' turn]]\n*[[Father of the House]]\n*[[Filial piety]]\n*[[Gerontocracy]]\n*[[Gerousia]]\n*[[Hierarchy]]\n*[[Lockstep compensation]]\n*[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives]]\n*[[Seniority in the United States Senate]]\n*[[Superior (hierarchy)]]\n*[[Tenure]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Political philosophy]]\n[[Category:Hierarchy]]\n[[Category:Personnel economics]]\n", "name_user": "132.147.16.91", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seniority"}
{"title_page": "Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox Olympic event\n| event       = Wrestling\n| games       = 1984 Summer\n| image       = Wrestling pictogram.svg\n| image_size  = 100px\n| venue       = [[Anaheim Convention Center]]\n| dates       = 30 July \u2013 11 August\n| competitors = 267\n| nations     = 44\n| prev        = [[Wrestling at the 1980 Summer Olympics|1980]]\n| next        = [[Wrestling at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988]]\n}}\n{{WrestlingAt1984SummerOlympics}}\nAt the '''[[1984 Summer Olympics]]''', 20 '''[[Amateur wrestling|wrestling]]''' events were contested. There were 10 weight classes in each of the [[freestyle wrestling]] and [[Greco-Roman wrestling]] disciplines.  Competition took place at the arena at the [[Anaheim Convention Center]] in [[Anaheim, California]].<ref name=\"SR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1984/WRE/ |title=Wrestling at the 1984 Los Angeles Summer Games |work=Sports Reference |accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Medal summary==\n===Freestyle===\n{| {{MedalistTable|type=Event}}\n|-\n| 48&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 48 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Bobby Weaver]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Takashi Irie]]|JPN|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Son Gab-Do]]|KOR|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 52&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 52 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[\u0160aban Trstena]]|YUG|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Kim Jong-kyu (wrestler)|Kim Jong-kyu]]|KOR|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Yuji Takada (wrestler)|Yuji Takada]]|JPN|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 57&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 57 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Hideaki Tomiyama]]|JPN|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Barry Davis (amateur wrestler)|Barry Davis]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Kim Eui-Kon]]|KOR|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 62&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 62 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Randy Lewis (wrestler)|Randall Lewis]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Kosei Akaishi]]|JPN|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Lee Jung-Keun]]|KOR|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 68&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 68 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[You In-Tak]]|KOR|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Andrew Rein]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Jukka Rauhala]]|FIN|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 74&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 74 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Dave Schultz (wrestling)|Dave Schultz]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Martin Knosp]]|FRG|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[\u0160aban Sejdi]]|YUG|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 82&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 82 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Mark Schultz (wrestler)|Mark Schultz]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Hideyuki Nagashima]]|JPN|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Christopher Rinke]]|CAN|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 90&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 90 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Ed Banach]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Akira Ota]]|JPN|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Noel Loban]]|GBR|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 100&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 100 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Lou Banach]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Joseph Atiyeh]]|SYR|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Vasile Pu\u0219ca\u0219u]]|ROU|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| +100&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle +100 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Bruce Baumgartner]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Robert Molle]]|CAN|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Ayhan Ta\u015fkin]]|TUR|1984 Summer}}\n|}\n\n===Greco-Roman===\n{| {{MedalistTable|type=Event}}\n|-\n| 48&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 48 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Vincenzo Maenza]]|ITA|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Markus Scherer]]|FRG|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Ikuzo Saito]]|JPN|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 52&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 52 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Atsuji Miyahara]]|JPN|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Daniel Aceves]]|MEX|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Bang Dae-Du]]|KOR|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 57&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 57 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Pasquale Passarelli]]|FRG|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Masaki Eto]]|JPN|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Charalambos Cholidis]]|GRE|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 62&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 62 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Kim Weon-Kee]]|KOR|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Kent-Olle Johansson]]|SWE|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Hugo Dietsche]]|SUI|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 68&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 68 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Vlado Lisjak]]|YUG|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Tapio Sipil\u00e4]]|FIN|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[James Martinez (wrestler)|James Martinez]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 74&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 74 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Jouko Salom\u00e4ki]]|FIN|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Roger Tallroth (wrestler)|Roger Tallroth]]|SWE|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[\u0218tefan Rusu]]|ROU|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 82&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 82 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Ion Draica]]|ROU|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Dimitrios Thanopoulos]]|GRE|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[S\u00f6ren Claeson]]|SWE|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 90&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 90 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Steve Fraser]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Ilie Matei]]|ROU|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Frank Andersson]]|SWE|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 100&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman 100 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Vasile Andrei]]|ROU|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Greg Gibson (wrestler)|Greg Gibson]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Jo\u017eef Tertei]]|YUG|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| +100&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's Greco-Roman +100 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Jeff Blatnick]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Refik Memi\u0161evi\u0107]]|YUG|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Victor Dolipschi]]|ROU|1984 Summer}}\n|}\n\n==Medal table==\n{{Medals table\n | caption        = \n | host           = \n | flag_template  = flagIOCteam\n | event          = 1984 Summer\n | team           = \n | gold_USA = 9 | silver_USA = 3 | bronze_USA = 1\n | gold_JPN = 2 | silver_JPN = 5 | bronze_JPN = 2\n | gold_KOR = 2 | silver_KOR = 1 | bronze_KOR = 4\n | gold_ROU = 2 | silver_ROU = 1 | bronze_ROU = 3\n | gold_YUG = 2 | silver_YUG = 1 | bronze_YUG = 2\n | gold_FRG = 1 | silver_FRG = 2 | bronze_FRG = 0\n | gold_FIN = 1 | silver_FIN = 1 | bronze_FIN = 1\n | gold_ITA = 1 | silver_ITA = 0 | bronze_ITA = 0\n | gold_SWE = 0 | silver_SWE = 2 | bronze_SWE = 2\n | gold_CAN = 0 | silver_CAN = 1 | bronze_CAN = 1\n | gold_GRE = 0 | silver_GRE = 1 | bronze_GRE = 1\n | gold_MEX = 0 | silver_MEX = 1 | bronze_MEX = 0\n | gold_SYR = 0 | silver_SYR = 1 | bronze_SYR = 0\n | gold_GBR = 0 | silver_GBR = 0 | bronze_GBR = 1\n | gold_SUI = 0 | silver_SUI = 0 | bronze_SUI = 1\n | gold_TUR = 0 | silver_TUR = 0 | bronze_TUR = 1\n}}\n\n==Participating nations==\n[[File:Lou Banach, Joseph Atiyeh and Vasile Pu\u0219ca\u0219u.jpg|thumb|Wrestlers greet the crowd at a medal ceremony.]]\nA total of 267 wrestlers from 44 nations competed at the Los Angeles Games:<ref name=\"SR\"/>\n{|\n|valign=top|\n*{{flagIOC|ARG|1984 Summer|3}}\n*{{flagIOC|AUS|1984 Summer|3}}\n*{{flagIOC|AUT|1984 Summer|7}}\n*{{flagIOC|BOL|1984 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|CMR|1984 Summer|5}}\n*{{flagIOC|CAN|1984 Summer|13}}\n*{{flagIOC|CHN|1984 Summer|7}}\n*{{flagIOC|TPE|1984 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|COL|1984 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|DOM|1984 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|ECU|1984 Summer|1}}\n|width=30|\n|valign=top|\n*{{flagIOC|EGY|1984 Summer|10}}\n*{{flagIOC|ESA|1984 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|FIN|1984 Summer|11}}\n*{{flagIOC|FRA|1984 Summer|8}}\n*{{flagIOC|GBR|1984 Summer|7}}\n*{{flagIOC|GRE|1984 Summer|10}}\n*{{flagIOC|IND|1984 Summer|8}}\n*{{flagIOC|IRQ|1984 Summer|3}}\n*{{flagIOC|ITA|1984 Summer|7}}\n*{{flagIOC|JPN|1984 Summer|20}}\n*{{flagIOC|LIB|1984 Summer|1}}\n|width=30|\n|valign=top|\n*{{flagIOC|MLT|1984 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|MTN|1984 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|MEX|1984 Summer|5}}\n*{{flagIOC|MAR|1984 Summer|5}}\n*{{flagIOC|NZL|1984 Summer|3}}\n*{{flagIOC|NGR|1984 Summer|3}}\n*{{flagIOC|NOR|1984 Summer|5}}\n*{{flagIOC|PAK|1984 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|PAN|1984 Summer|1}}\n*{{flagIOC|PER|1984 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|PUR|1984 Summer|3}}\n|width=30|\n|valign=top|\n*{{flagIOC|ROU|1984 Summer|10}}\n*{{flagIOC|SEN|1984 Summer|4}}\n*{{flagIOC|KOR|1984 Summer|14}}\n*{{flagIOC|ESP|1984 Summer|3}}\n*{{flagIOC|SWE|1984 Summer|11}}\n*{{flagIOC|SUI|1984 Summer|2}}\n*{{flagIOC|SYR|1984 Summer|3}}\n*{{flagIOC|TUR|1984 Summer|16}}\n*{{flagIOC|USA|1984 Summer|19}}\n*{{flagIOC|FRG|1984 Summer|14}}\n*{{flagIOC|YUG|1984 Summer|9}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Wrestling at the Friendship Games]]\n* [[List of World and Olympic Champions in men's freestyle wrestling]]\n* [[List of World and Olympic Champions in Greco-Roman wrestling]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite web | title=Olympic Medal Winners | publisher=[[International Olympic Committee]] |url=http://www.olympic.org/uk/athletes/results/search_r_uk.asp | accessdate=1 January 2007 }}\n\n{{EventsAt1984SummerOlympics}}\n{{Wrestling at the Summer Olympics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wrestling At The 1984 Summer Olympics}}\n[[Category:1984 in sport wrestling]]\n[[Category:1984 Summer Olympics events]]\n[[Category:Wrestling at the Summer Olympics|1984]]\n[[Category:Wrestling in Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox Olympic event\n| event       = Wrestling\n| games       = 1984 Summer\n| image       = Wrestling pictogram.svg\n| image_size  = 100px\n| venue       = [[Anaheim Convention Center]]\n| dates       = 30 July \u2013 11 August\n| competitors = 267\n| nations     = 44\n| prev        = [[Wrestling at the 1980 Summer Olympics|1980]]\n| next        = [[Wrestling at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988]]\n}}\n{{WrestlingAt1984SummerOlympics}}\nAt the '''[[1984 Summer Olympics]]''', 20 '''[[Amateur wrestling|wrestling]]''' events were contested. There were 10 weight classes in each of the [[freestyle wrestling]] and [[Greco-Roman wrestling]] disciplines.  Competition took place at the arena at the [[Anaheim Convention Center]] in [[Anaheim, California]].<ref name=\"SR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1984/WRE/ |title=Wrestling at the 1984 Los Angeles Summer Games |work=Sports Reference |accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Medal summary==\n===Freestyle===\n{| {{MedalistTable|type=Event}}\n|-\n| 48&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 48 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Bobby Weaver]]|USA|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Takashi Irie]]|JPN|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Son Gab-Do]]|KOR|1984 Summer}}\n|-\n| 52&nbsp;kg<br>{{DetailsLink|Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 52 kg}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[\u0160aban Trstena]]|YUG|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Kim Jong-kyu (wrestler)|Kim Jong-kyu]]|KOR|1984 Summer}}\n|{{flagIOCathlete|[[Yuji Takada